House Price Prediction Project¶

Danxuan Han¶

This project is stemed from one of the Kaggle's competitions- House Prices: Advanced Regression Techniques.
To dig into the problem, I studied some notes from kaggle's kernel, inspired by their methods, I generated my own research report.

References:
1.Comprehensive data exploration with Python--provides elegant Python code to visualize data
2.A study on Regression applied to the Ames dataset--provides some ideas of feature constructing, and dealing with missing value
3.XGBoost + Lasso--provides good idea to process feature's data
4.Stacked Regression: Top 4% on LeaderBoard--good and comprehensive example for data processing, feature engineering
5.Handling missing values--talking about advantages and shortcomings of some different ways to deal with missing values, although not comprehensive enough

Converting the string values features into numerical features¶

First, converting the intensy leveled categorical features into numerical features.
By stating "intensy leveled " I mean that those features could be quantified, for example, for the feature of "Alley", I could set gravel to 1, pave to 2 and no alley for 0, it means that pave alley will be 2 times than gravel. But for the feature of MSZoning, it has different values of "A", "C", "FV" etc, representing different zonging classification, so I couldn't set them from 1 to 3, because "C" shouldn't represent 2 times of A. So, in the first place, I just want to convert some categorical features which could be quantified directly. For other categorical features, I could add more features of dummy variables or just ignore them, this will be dealed later.

In [19]:

Some explainations about the feature process:

1.Utilities: AllPub means have all public utilities, including electricity, water, gas, sewer, and other values mean lacking utilities, so the descending sort of 4, 3, 2, 1 may could better explain the completeness of utility and help to explain the house price. Same as LotShape.
2.Fence: means fence quality, but the explaination in the txt file actually combined two categories into one, it includes the information of both privacy and the fence material, so, I decided to let it become a dummy variable, have fence: 1, no fence: 0.
3.MiscVal, MiscFeature: MiscVal means value of miscellaneous feature, MiscFeature means if the house has elevator, shed or other miscellaneous feature, so I could just use MiscVal and delete feature of MiscFeature

Process numerical data¶

First, we should figure out some seemingly numerical data are actually categorical data. For instance, MoSold, which means Month Sold (MM), the feature's values arange from 1 to 12, but 12 actually doesn't mean 12 times of 1, so we should be aware of those seemingly numerical features first.

In [21]:
# 1.YearBuilt, YearRemodAdd, MoSold, YrSold:  
# For MoSold, maybe Months with the largest number of deals are significant, or maybe it is better to delete 
# this feature.
# Construct a new feature of age of house, use YrSold-YearBuilt, and delete YearBuilt, since we want to remain the
# influence of market price inflation, so I think YrSold is still useful
df_train["HouseAge"] = df_train["YrSold"] - df_train["YearBuilt"]
df_train.drop(["YearBuilt","YearRemodAdd","MoSold"], axis=1, inplace=True)

# 2.BsmtUnfSF, BsmtFinSF1, BsmtFinSF2: BsmtUnfSF means unfinished area of basement, BsmtFinSF1 means finished area, 
# they contain the same information, so we could delete the feature of BsmtUnfSF  
df_train.drop(["BsmtUnfSF"], axis=1, inplace=True)

Pay Attention to Target Variable -SalePrice¶

When we research in variables like sales and wages, sometimes people tend to do log-transformation (for ranges could be from minus infinity to positive infinity, not just positive). Doing log-transformation on dependent variable could lessen the problem of heteroscedasticity, also, followed by computation of a geometric mean ratio (rather than a mean difference.) So, I tend to do log-transformation on the SalePrice.

In [25]:
df_train.SalePrice = np.log1p(df_train.SalePrice)

Use the heatmap to see correlation between SalePrice and other features, and some highly correlated pairs.

From the above correlation map and rank, we could find most correlated numerical features, we could focus on, for example, set the thresholds of corr > 0.3 and corr < -0.3. And then, we could look at the categorical features.

By setting thresholds of 0.3 and -0.3, we found the most important features: OverallQual, GrLivArea, GarageCars, ExterQual, KitchenQual, GarageArea, BsmtQual, TotalBsmtSF, GarageFinish, 1stFlrSF, FullBath, TotRmsAbvGrd, Fireplaces, HeatingQC, MasVnrArea, BsmtFinSF1, BsmtExposure, WoodDeckSF, OpenPorchSF, 2ndFlrSF, BsmtFinType1, HalfBath, PavedDrive, and one minus correlated variable of HouseAge.

Further Tailor Features and Process Data (detect and process outliers etc.)¶

After selecting these important features, we should further research if some features could be simplified, maybe they contain same information (so may cause multicollinearity, but multicollinearity doesn't affect final predictions precision, it just affects coefficient and p values, so I just ignored the multicollinearity problem at here), maybe we could contruct more features to do better prediction.

In [27]:
# selecting those important features
import_num_features = corrmat.SalePrice[[corrmat.SalePrice.iloc[i]>0.3 or corrmat.SalePrice.iloc[i]<-0.3 \
                                         for i in range(len(corrmat.SalePrice))]].index

# show the heatmap of correlation of those important features
cm2 = df_train[import_num_features].corr()

                 yticklabels=import_num_features.values, xticklabels=import_num_features.values)
plt.show()

From this heatmap, we could detect highly correlated important numerical features pairs. First, we should set a threshold, for example, 0.6

In [28]:
# find highly correlated (>0.6 or <-0.6) pairs
pairs_ls = []
for i in range(len(cm2.columns)):
    for j in range(i):
        if (cm2.iloc[j,i] > 0.6 or cm2.iloc[j,i] < -0.6):
            pairs_ls.append(cm2.index[j] + "-" + cm2.columns[i])
